Title: Crush
Info / Notes / Links: cold wave music with creepy monophonic vocals overtop distorted, crushed guitars and synths and some simplistic drum-machine beats. g od for my public shame and white lodge/black lodge

Title: The Year Of The Fish
Info / Notes / Links: loud alternative rock with walls of guitar, big drum sounds and distorted vocals

Title: The Suburbs
Info / Notes / Links: pop songs with a great beat for indie dance parties and teen sentiments out the whazoo

Title: Specific, Northwest
Info / Notes / Links: darlingly, delightful indie-pop love ballads... the soundtrack for you life, really. good for music to my ears and william tell

Title: Expansion Pack
Info / Notes / Links: comical metal/rock band. blips, boops, crazy neon. great for mind graps. awesome for my allergy to the fans as well

Title: Butterflies & Zebras
Info / Notes / Links: this band creates psychedelic, instrumental ambience. the sounds are super spaced out and create something to get lost in on a long afternoon. pretty good for katharsis or attention surplus disorder

Title: Dirty Dance Party
Info / Notes / Links: ridiculously cheesy music up the alley of har mar superstar with ridiculous casio sounds creating a dirty dance party indeed. a ton of fun. good for 2 and 2 ain't 5

Title: The Central Nervous System
Info / Notes / Links: electro-rock with some good beats and some cool effects. the vocals and song structure remind me a little bit of sloan. there are a few fun songs that twilight banter might get a kick out of.

Title: Warm Weather With Ryan Driver
Info / Notes / Links: a simple collection of brilliant songwriting with a french flair and a dash of interesting electronic drones. Good for the mornings. (http://www.myspace.com/ericchenaux)

Title: Ivory Tower
Info / Notes / Links: hitting pretty much every genre, gonzales shows a flare for songwriting and composition.

Title: The Great Depression
Info / Notes / Links: a playful and incredibly diverse collection of indie-pop with really intelligent songwriting. good for advance cassette

Title: Come The Day
Info / Notes / Links: very jazz-influenced soul/rock record. features female vocals with the odd male vocal rap. a slight twist in another direction and this would be a full-blown jazz cd

Title: Wires
Info / Notes / Links: intense, hella-loud rock that has more twists and turns than disneyland. some songs have rap over raw punk rock then the next will settle into loose country rock. settle in for a good ride. (http://www.cowlick.ca/rock.html)

Title: Talk - Action = 0
Info / Notes / Links: what do you expect? the same old d.o.a that punks have grown up with. it's pretty energetic and definitely hardcore. good for blue collar bravado and graveyard riot

Title: Everything Is Fine
Info / Notes / Links: pretty charming and kind of gritty alt-rock

Title: Stereophonic Tonic
Info / Notes / Links: endearingly sloppy punk rock with a lots of grunge and a little glam to add highlights. great for graveyard riot. (http://www.myspace.com/durbanfnpoison)

Title: Revenge
Info / Notes / Links: without any clear intention towards one style of music, end of the world 1969 do some styles well and other styles so so. pretty decent folk, kind of sweet casio-core and fantastic fuzzy rock. (http://www.myspace.com/endoftheworld1969)

Title: Think About It
Info / Notes / Links: straight forward indie pop (http://www.myspace.com/thefalklands)

Title: Coat of Arms
Info / Notes / Links: fun indie rock with a 60s doo-wop/psychedelic influence and just a bunch of interesting tid-bits. sounds a bit like new pornographers and cuff the duke. good for aubrey's shindig and advance cassette.

Title: The Goodtimes
Info / Notes / Links: almost satirical electro-pop making fun that might be making fun of the 80s childishly simple beats and melodies... that said, the songs are really fun, groovy and unique with lots of good movers and shakers. i think road pops will take to it.

Title: Dig Your Own Grave
Info / Notes / Links: rockabilly and punk, very bluesy, gritty and all together morbid. great for graveyard riot and blue collar bravado

Title: Someone, Somewhere, Somehow
Info / Notes / Links: a range of alternative country ballads. you've got heavy songs, psychedelic songs and slow songs. what ties them all together is a country twang and acoustic instrumentation. blue collar bravado may like it. good for day time shows too

Title: The Lion's Tooth
Info / Notes / Links: happy go lucky pop songs. great for daydream dance party

Title: Louder Faster More Fun
Info / Notes / Links: awesome high energy punk rock, with shades of psychobilly. good for graveyard riot, who let me on the radio and my allergy to the fans

Title: Cloak and Cipher
Info / Notes / Links: a taste of romantic indie- rock with lush harmonies and driving melodies played with just enough distortion. great for instant gratification revoked and double entendre preserves

Title: Some move Closer, Some Move On
Info / Notes / Links: following in the footsteps of the psych-folk movement, lauren makes some beautiful and very memorable songs. very good for katharsis. (http://www.giannalauren.ca/)

Title: Dependent Arising
Info / Notes / Links: a fragile voice accompanied by only the simplest instruments makes folk songs that'll touch your heart and bring light to the dark places. really nice. really good for some of the day time shows and double entendre preserves may like it

Title: Comfortable Dungeon
Info / Notes / Links: cute indie rock with happy summer vibes, lots of crazy synth sounds and an overall kind of twee feeling. Good for the chit chat

Title: Peace Maker
Info / Notes / Links: while eamon has an overarching acoustic feel there are some serious rockers on this album with complete explosions of bass, guitar and drums. a good try for pretty much any show especially my allergy to the fans

Title: Sunset Sea
Info / Notes / Links: lively island-sounding tunes. similar to joel plaskett. good for soapbox derby

Title: The Thing
Info / Notes / Links: strongly african (fela!)- influenced music, with some reggae, coupled with pop/rock style lyrics and vocals (though not too conventional). works not too badly.

Title: Lay It On Me
Info / Notes / Links: rock with a little billy, or maybe billy with a little rock. sounds like some good foot-stompin' country with some loud instrumentation giving it a pretty heavy edge. good for pillage the village and bikesheviks

Title: All The Things We've Been Told
Info / Notes / Links: an absolutely adorable pack of songs, very very upbeat and happy. great for fans of the new pornographers

Title: Watcha Doin' Baby?
Info / Notes / Links: soul-spun pop with a hint of 80s synth-pop and all around good feelings. the kind of thing her royal opinion and breaking techniques will dig.

Title: Supermagique
Info / Notes / Links: a worldy pop album that's almost too sweet and darling at times, sounding a lot like sarah mclachlin era female vocal bands.

Title: Waikiki
Info / Notes / Links: dazzling and whimsical indie-folk songs with some very french sounding instrumentation and a couple songs in french. great for french transe and danse.

Title: Meet Me At The Muster Station
Info / Notes / Links: For only two guys, this band has a really full sound that capitalizes on lo-fi. sounds kind of like frog eyes. great for music to my ears and my allergy to the fans.

Title: Lights From Paradise
Info / Notes / Links: overall a fairly psychedelic album with hints of rockabilly in the uber fuzzy guitar riffs. then add a very melancholy vocalist and you've got a pretty sweet band. good for each one teach one and who let me on the radio.

Title: Breaking Hearts
Info / Notes / Links: ecstatic and bouncy power-pop

Title: The Record Holder
Info / Notes / Links: a collection of bittersweet songs, very mellow. good for the morning

Title: Candle To Your Eyes
Info / Notes / Links: indie rock that really pushes on, rocks out and provides whimsy to your day

Title: Siskiyou
Info / Notes / Links: adorable indie songs kept minimal and lo-fi with a great singer-songwriter feel (http://www.myspace.com/siskiyou)

Title: Sweet Thing
Info / Notes / Links: the tracks on this compilation are mostly fairly beat-heavy with r+b influences and, often,other elements (dub or reggae or jazz or rap or middle eastern) added. The stuff is slickly produced, some of it too much so. ()

Title: For Posterity
Info / Notes / Links: experimental noise-rock that's more just weird than it is gritty. it flirts with metal, prog-metal and alternative sounds. each one, teach one could give it a try, as could white lodge/black lodge and mind grapes

Title: I Feel GoodÉ.
Info / Notes / Links: lo-fi alt-rock with lots of spaced out choruses and drowned vocals

Title: The Days of Blinding Fear
Info / Notes / Links: really fun selection of rockin' songs that keep it really bright and sunny. they have a nice *almost folky angle to them

Title: Young Man
Info / Notes / Links: rough and tumble, well produced rock songs. hurricane hannah might dig it. (http://www.sweetthingmusic.com/bio/)

Title: The Viking
Info / Notes / Links: grungy rock music with a very fine hint of country flair. (http://treelinesmusic.com/)

Title: Our Post Is Bronzed
Info / Notes / Links: country-blues-rock with distortion layered overtop. kind of eccentric. (http://www.myspace.com/garrettcraigswhiskeyface)

Title: It's The Evil
Info / Notes / Links: really, really awesome thrashing punk. super fast licks meet in your face presence. great for each one, teach one.

Title: Rain & Pocket Change
Info / Notes / Links: very cute indie-rock complete with glockenspiel, upbeat guitar and romantic, youthful lyrics. good for white lodge/black lodge

Title: All Red
Info / Notes / Links: chip and cheerful indie rock with a postal service vibe. lots of indie rock sounds like reverb drenched synths and tambourines

Title: Milk
Info / Notes / Links: straying away from his usual rock, this album is just as sexy with the 80s synth-pop turned up to take it up to a whip it or kylie minogue level. some of you might get a kick out of it even though it is right on the cusp of being too mainstream

Title: Game Changer
Info / Notes / Links: downtempo trance songs with some pretty weird samples and loops going down. great for french transe and dance

Title: Beast Rest Forth Mouth Remixed
Info / Notes / Links: beautiful, breathy indie-electro songs along the lines of m83 and caribou. good for twilight banter and radio boys.

Title: Lowell Bekker
Info / Notes / Links: really really cheesy robot-electronica. a little bit like beastie boys. good for bryson

Title: Celebrity Traffic
Info / Notes / Links: something between punk and straight up electro, i guess it's called electro-punk. gritty synths drill out catchy melodies while drum machines drive home the deep basslines. pretty crazy stuff. good for fullmoon funkalicious and radio boys and tea time with annie

Title: Loop Over Latitudes
Info / Notes / Links: ambient electronica that utilizes found sounds and time-stretching techniques to create lush compositions. great for post everything.

Title: Black City
Info / Notes / Links: electronica that goes way left- field for beats that are syncopated and idealic. Great for funk sunden.

Title: Say Goodbye To Useless
Info / Notes / Links: grimey break beats layered with ambient, spooky sounds and scratches. definitely bordering a good boundary. kind of like flying lotus and blockhead. good for tea time with annie.

Title: Ventricle
Info / Notes / Links: actual drifting electronics create complex soundscapes here with a variety of intricate sounds. some songs have more breaks (track #3) but most are very ambient

Title: XXX
Info / Notes / Links: an assortment of done-before electronic dance tracks. track 5 is an awesome idm track. most of the others are pretty clubby.

Title: Music For Paradise Armor
Info / Notes / Links: reaching out into the realm of early electronics and musique concrete, this disc is definitely a worhwhile listen for the experimental minded

Title: Remixes Vol-1
Info / Notes / Links: heavy, hard-hitting ebm - great selection of stompy songs. good for bassackwards and could even fit in with some d 'n' b

Title: Mania
Info / Notes / Links: cut straight to the pounding, heavy beats of the bangin' club scene! LeBeato's stuff is super fun and perfect for a dance party with sounds drenched in vocoder and synth effects

Title: Twelve Remixes Of Four Songs
Info / Notes / Links: indie dance pop remixes of ok go. lots of cool effects ad some cool beats. (http://www.okgo.net/)

Title: Church With No Magic
Info / Notes / Links: right up the Warp alley, this album is so expansive with some absolutely amazing electronic sound-scapes. recommended for white lodge/black lodge

Title: Spirit In The System
Info / Notes / Links: very very well produced edgy electronica. far heavier than any electroclash. for fans of the presets and bloodhound gang. good for late night friday. (http://www.myspace.com/qemists)

Title: It Takes A Thief
Info / Notes / Links: these boys bring a brazilian flare to their trip-hoppin' dub stylings that end up littered all over the map. great for the road pops

Title: Vegetables
Info / Notes / Links: big beat styled club tracks produced by a local celebrity, Dominic Pierce, and a collection of songs from many electronic tastes.

Title: Devil You're A Liar
Info / Notes / Links: chill-out music with dark shades that carve out a futuristic soundscape for people who like nightmares on wax. some of the jazzier tracks will be good for the chit chat, while others will be nice on tea time with annie and funk senden

Title: Blood
Info / Notes / Links: darkwave/lo-fi industrial and really beat-heavy with little to no vocals. good for bassackwards and new classics

Title: The Paradigm Shift
Info / Notes / Links: a solid house mix of groovy, consistent beats. good for sunday night groove school

Title: Music For Dreaming & Playing
Info / Notes / Links: ambient and glitchy electro-acoustic compositions. these electronic sound-scapes are as beautiful as anything kettel or secede could come up with. wow. great for post-everything and katharsis

Title: Infra
Info / Notes / Links: ambient, sweeping neo-classical compositions. good for white lodge/black lodge, katharsis and that's classical

Title: Tibi
Info / Notes / Links: music played on sardinian prepared guitar. at times

Title: PsstÉPsst!
Info / Notes / Links: experimental sounds from a quartet playing a somewhat odd selection of instruments. there's a hint of jazz here and there but it's mostly in a classical view. track #11 is a remix of a radiohead song. (http://www.myspace.com/betacollide)

Title: All Is Falling
Info / Notes / Links: beautiful neo-classical compositions with some cool bagpipe sounds on some of the later half. perfect for that's classical? (http://www.myspace.com/jamesblackshaw)

Title: Aim For The Roses
Info / Notes / Links: creepy spoken work crawling overtop of neo-classical, er, experimental compositions. very interesting. good for noise and twisted brain wrong andthe two and two ain't five show (http://www.myspace.com/hotardentzeal)

Title: A Little Dark Music
Info / Notes / Links: contemporary classical compositions that are slow and mellow fire kind of music. bryson describes it as doogie howser meets glenn gould. good for between the lines.

Title: Pinnacles
Info / Notes / Links: minimal neo-classical compositions with such a sparseness that they give off a certain eeriness. perfect for between the lines.

Title: Open
Info / Notes / Links: bass clarinetist with a knack for experimental neo-classical compositions. great for between the lines.

Title: Sunless/Ellipses, Lapses and Collapses
Info / Notes / Links: quiet and subdued compositions in ambience. Great for katharsis

Title: Queen Mary Trash
Info / Notes / Links: a blend of off the beaten path folk and slow alternative rock songs (http://www.myspace.com/wartornman)

Title: Dawn Time Riot
Info / Notes / Links: a collection of happy folk songs with intense harmonies. imagine the polyphonic spree took to more rootsy songs. good for soapbox derby and double entendre preserves.

Title: Paupers Field
Info / Notes / Links: a debut album that couldn't sound more well-composed and experienced. americana songs with quite stirring instrumentation that will run romantic thoughts across your mind

Title: Dog Weather
Info / Notes / Links: a flavourful mix of folk tunes, some are heavy, some are pretty reflective and some sound slightly more pop. all with a good message.

Title: I Can Too
Info / Notes / Links: a great selection of original folk songs with a real good drive. similar to lucinda williams. good for alternative to what? and the morning after. (http://www.myspace.com/cpmartin)

Title: Tailored to Fit
Info / Notes / Links: a small collection of utterly heartbreaking folk songs. (http://www.myspace.com/markberubemusic)

Title: To The Last Drop
Info / Notes / Links: a variety of rootsy folk songs with a good slow- country edge singing about the prairies. some songs will really suit tombstone after dark while others will be great for soapbox derby.

Title: In Defence Of The Wild
Info / Notes / Links: an environmental activist puts together thought-provoking folk songs with a dourness similar to Morrissey. great for soapbox derby

Title: Eastward + Onward
Info / Notes / Links: boot-scootin' boogie-woogie country music, very rootsy and lots of traditional instrumentation

Title: I Would Rather Go Blind
Info / Notes / Links: country blues boys doing a bunch of covers including one of the rolling stones and putting a bluesy edge on it. very talented bunch of musicians. good for the blues witness.

Title: The Well
Info / Notes / Links: exceptional, old- time blues complete with swingin' harmonica lines and wonderful, bluesy guitar. perfect for the blues witness and morning after.

Title: The Courage, The Strength, The Wisdom, The Doubt
Info / Notes / Links: folk-rock songs with a pretty happy air surrounding them

Title: Follow Your Bliss
Info / Notes / Links: folky songs with senior talent on the writing, incorporating various elements of worldly folk. good for soapbox derby and alternative to what (http://www.myspace.com/pogirls)

Title: The Hobo Son
Info / Notes / Links: good old timey country music with a real willie nelson kind of vibe. good for tombstone after dark.

Title: The Trick With Your Heart I'm Learning To Do
Info / Notes / Links: heart-warming Americana songs, written with lots of touching emotion and a few thought-provoking themes

Title: Three Penny Opus
Info / Notes / Links: homey, roots country. really mellow and lovely stuff

Title: Steel City Trawler
Info / Notes / Links: nitty gritty folk. the acoustic bits are sentimental. the rock bits are edgy, giving a facelift to the old-thyme sound. (http://www.myspace.com/lukedoucet)

Title: Georgia Warhorse
Info / Notes / Links: old- time blues music with a polished feel. great delivery all the way around and pretty engaging stuff. good for s. Louisiana gumbo.

Title: Wild Rose Sorrow
Info / Notes / Links: pretty sorrowful folk-rock for the most part, mopey but also very very beautiful. in the kind of cuff the duke and eamon mcgrath

Title: Strawberry Moon
Info / Notes / Links: really pretty, simple songs with a carol king kind of sound.

Title: The High Road Home
Info / Notes / Links: really upbeat, fun and fast roots-folk. perfect for the folkcetera show. (http://www.jackwilliamsmusic.com/)

Title: Deadmalls & Nightfalls
Info / Notes / Links: rootsy folk tunes with a modern edge. good for soap box and her royal opinion.

Title: First Sound
Info / Notes / Links: simple, singer- songwriter stuff with an emphasis on strong songwriting in line with daniel johnston (yes, almost indie in flavour) but also with a good swing. really good for the morning shows.

Title: Howlin' At The Moon
Info / Notes / Links: the kind of country-rockin' that you'd hear in a small town bar. a group of musicians who are super skilled and make beautiful, full sounds come out of every instrument and voice

Title: Tall Hours In The Glowstream
Info / Notes / Links: very well composed folk songs that sound aged in a vintage spirit and packed full of powerful messages. good for soapbox derby and even music to my ears might enjoy it for being off the beaten path

Title: Absence Of Blame
Info / Notes / Links: well composed country music with strong messages and interesting instrumentation. more on the pop side of country than the rootsy side

Title: Sand & Lines
Info / Notes / Links: wilco-esque folk tunes with a great pop flavour and some old-timey feelings stuck in for good measure

Title: Manic Almanac: Slow Mobius
Info / Notes / Links: instrumental folk music with a broad range of influences from avant to celtic. good for alternative to what?

Title: Two Pieces
Info / Notes / Links: a real belter singing gypsy folk waltzes and regina spektor-esque vocals. cool use of instruments for sure. good for the chit chat

Title: Old Devils
Info / Notes / Links: a weirdo kind of roots music. sure, it has acoustic instruments and a gruff Jon Langford on vox, but the compositions are surely unique. signs of celtic folk surface, as does rockabilly and doo wop. great for tombstone after dark, blue collar bravado & the two and two ain't five show

Title: Secrets
Info / Notes / Links: a wonderful and jazzy voice belting out really chill songs. good for her royal opinion and cold smoke

Title: Viper At The Virgin's Feet
Info / Notes / Links: bluegrass tunes sung solo by a pretty talented lady on guitar, ukulele and a cast of backing musicians armed with all the rootsy instruments. good for folkcetera

Title: Believe It Or Not, This Is The Place
Info / Notes / Links: dream-folk artist here, incredibly sad-sounding songs sun over full orchestral sounds. beautiful composition, lots of things you wouldn't expect and makes you ask what you're hearing and where's that sound coming from. great for katharsis.

Title: Move The Earth
Info / Notes / Links: east coast country music that sings of a rich history. very classic and good for folkcetera

Title: Palace In The Sun
Info / Notes / Links: full and upbeat folk-rock songs with fantastic beats and exceptionally good refrains

Title: 180 South: Conquerors Of The Useless
Info / Notes / Links: melancholy, ambient songs that adeptly create a lonely soundscape. a few of the songs are a little more folky.

Title: No Loitering
Info / Notes / Links: open-mic kind of singer-songwriter stuff but really thoughtful, pensive and unique.

Title: Modern Field Recordings
Info / Notes / Links: rootsy and yet a quanitly indie collection of quiet songs perfect for cabins on quiet lakes. good for cold smoke

Title: I Tried
Info / Notes / Links: sad songs reminding me of rufus wainwright probably because of the complex piano melodies. good for some of the morning shows

Title: The Farmer
Info / Notes / Links: this seasoned musician brings an indie sensibility along to create catchy folk songs.

Title: The Poet & The Maiden
Info / Notes / Links: very mellow acoustic songs, a couple (ie track 2) are kind of strange interpretation of folk, but most songs are kind of on the boring side

Title: Shannon Stephens
Info / Notes / Links: well-written, heartfelt songs with a old-time feel. good for folkcetera and my public shame

Title: After-Birth Of Cool
Info / Notes / Links: a short cd (just over 28 mins) featuring vibes, bass, and drums, with the vibes strongly in the lead (no other instrument solos). the vibes are used much like a fender rhodes would be in the tunes.

Title: Live! A Weekend at Centre St. Ambroise
Flights: Volume One
Info / Notes / Links: flugelhorn and guitar pieces with other instruments on some tracks. it's melodic but mostly not mushy.

Title: Don't Call Her Larry: Volume 3: American Roots
Info / Notes / Links: songs in a variety of styles with simple instrumentation backing (some times just a bass, for instance) some songs work better than others.

Title: Lloyd Miller & The Heliocentrics
Info / Notes / Links: small group (trio?) jazz with middle eastern and asian melodies and instrumentation. the bass player lays down great grooves on most of the tracks.

Title: Introducing Takao Iwaki
Info / Notes / Links: very straight-ahead, melodic quartet jazz (sax, piano, bass, drums) it's kind of drab but there is the odd nice touch

Title: New Sounds Of Exotica
Info / Notes / Links: lounge jazz with jungle and latin sounds. nothing really stands out too much but there's nothing really bad either.

Artist: Raegele, Steve w/ Thom Gossage & Miles Perkin
Title: Last Century
Info / Notes / Links: guitar- bass- drums trio playing either spacey, more atmospheric tunes or spacey, jerky pieces. guitar is definitely at the centre of things

Artist: Etoroma, Efa Jr. / Efa Etoroma Jr. Trio
Title: Before & After
Info / Notes / Links: piano- bass- drums trio playing melodic, somewhat repetitive (as the cd goes on) jazz. this would just be fair stuff if it were not for the drummer, who adds an extra dimension to the proceedings.

Title: The New York Contemporary Five
Info / Notes / Links: recorded in 1963 released in 1967 and re-released in 2010. this is avant-leaning jazz, a good example of that sort of sound from the early '60s (http://www.archieshepp.net/)

Title: Chamber Music Society
Info / Notes / Links: the most prominent things here are spalding's voice and strings that appear throughout the cd (hence, the chamber music bit). nothing mind-blowing but nothing bad either though things start sounding the same after a while. (http://www.esperanzaspalding.com/)

Title: Fused Jazz
Info / Notes / Links: twelve piano and bass duets with the piano taking the lead (the bass is kinda muted it would have been nice to have it higher in the mix) Not exceptional but not bad either)

Title: Revisit
Info / Notes / Links: trumpet and percussion and moog. a good combination that is often melodic, catchy, and spacey at the same time. (http://www.myspace.com/mikrokolektyw)

Title: Vignettes
Info / Notes / Links: very straight-ahead quartet (saxest plute/piano/bass/drums) music. nothing special but nothing bad, a few nice features here and there. (http://www.scottdouglasmarshall.com/home.html)

Title: The Sound Of Rhythm & Culture
Info / Notes / Links: ethereal pop songs with beats bordering on funk and songs just up beat enough to get in your head. lovely stuff for daydream dance party (http://www.myspace.com/thetwinshadow)

Title: You Are there
Info / Notes / Links: piano/vocal duets of standard songs

Title: Peppermint Kush / Kush à la Menthe
The Ropes That Bind
Info / Notes / Links:
Richard Reynolds got ahold of us via our facebook (is that correct? maybe Facebook should be capitalized? Our editor is doing a liquor run, so we can't check with him right now) page, and has sent us some 80's electronica. We're pretty impressed by this stuff - Calgary's always been a rawk town, so this really is a part of the underground.

This tape is a collaboration of sorts between Reynolds (brokenpaws) and Mikel Weicker (Weep O Mine Eyes). Reynolds tells us that the tape was recorded in both of their home studios they got to use two tracks each on a 4-track machine, combining them together to form one track. It's kid of hard to fathom how this would have come together over 20 years ago.

Reynolds has pointed us to some reviews of the tape from back in the day, and also some of his and Weicker's more recent (relatively) involvement in the local electronica scene. 

http://calgarycassettes.blogspot.com/2010/03/wings-heaven-brokenpaws-and-weep-o-mine.html

Title: Stop Staring At The Ground
Info / Notes / Links:
http://calgarycassettes.blogspot.com/2009/12/sky-suspended-stop-staring-at-ground.html

We've been a bit lax with posting over the past few days, mostly because of the usual seasonal eating/drinking cycles we've fallen into here at the CCPS. So we're pleased to present this for your consideration, the second Sky Suspended tape.

Sky Suspended prompt us to ask several questions. First, how did Aaron Booth turn from this (we'll call it Disintegration-era Cure) to the sensitive singer-songwriter type? Second, how did Aaron Smelski go from bass with this to shoegaze guitar with Hot Little Rocket and heat-ray? And finally, what is up with all the Teddy Boys on the inner sleeve?

Title: This Is What They Call The Life
Demo 1997
Info / Notes / Links:
We've pulled together three demo tapes from the New Internationalists into one collection here, partly to show how much a band can change over time (especially with changes in membership) and partly because we're quite lazy.

The first few songs on here fit the same style as the tape we featured yesterday our Musical Analogue Expert wants to compare these guys to Hunters and Collectors without the horn section. We're still trying to figure out how we ended up with a position called a Musical Analogue Expert. We think he's referring to the anthemic, big music sound they put out. Anyhow, we found a bio of frontman Bruce Callow that indicates he split town and headed to Costa Rica, where he's been since. After the first tape, the style of this changes radically - ending in pretty uninteresting blues rock (to us - but then, we've never like the blues). We were overly-quick in returning the tapes we borrowed from CJSW back to Myke Atkinson we neglected to make any notes of who the members were for the final two tapes.

The same bio of Bruce Callow indicates that the New Internationalists reunited sometime after 2003, and put out a CD.

But, again, we don't really care about CDs here. 

http://calgarycassettes.blogspot.com/2010/02/new-internationalists-cjsw-demos-1992.html

Title: The End Of Decency
Info / Notes / Links:
http://calgarycassettes.blogspot.com/2009/12/teens-for-decency-end-of-decency-1997.html

We posted the first TFD tape quite a while back. For this outing, they're sporting a new bassist and drummer (Corey Martens went onto infamy with Helvis). The first side of this tape are studio tracks, but it's the second side, recorded live at the Night Gallery, that gives a better taste of hee-haw punk rawk flavour of these guys, as well as showing off Ian Doig's penchant for telling very strange historical tales.

As an aside, this tape is another we've borrowed from the CJSW archives. We'll be back at CJSW tomorrow, on our pal Adam Kamis' show, the Failed Pilot (12-2 pm MST), playing some of our favourite tapes. Which means it'll be a solid two hours of Primrods. And maybe a bit of Brass.

Info / Notes / Links: (http://www.myspace.com/thejoehiphop)

Info / Notes / Links: definitely neo-classical with strings (piano, violin) and horns (clarinet, flute, trumpet). good for between the lines. (http://homepage.mac.com/james.harley/)

Title: PY
Info / Notes / Links: an incredible selection of folk songs inspired from every corner of the world from africa to brazil to greece. a really amazing selection. there are songs for the likes of breaking the tethers all the way to via lactea caboose. (http://www.myspace.com/jaymestone)

Title: Secret Shock
Info / Notes / Links: a variety of slightly twisted music here, jazz-based but also reflecting r+b and rock. vocals on most tracks, including some by big-name singers like elvis costello, deborah harry (http://www.jazzpassengers.com/)

Title: One Of Us
Info / Notes / Links: amazing funk-soul revolution over here. it's so deep and funky and perfect for am mixtape right through to musiquarium (http://wakeup.johnlegend.com/)

Title: Point A To Point A
Info / Notes / Links: probably the best danser album I've heard yet. a good bluesy rhythm throughout and that deep, deep voice. lovely. good for folkcetera (http://www.myspace.com/katdanser)

Title: The Diary of the Unforgotten: Selbstportrait VI
Info / Notes / Links: fuzzy, lo-fi junky pop that's really sparse. good for daytime.

Title: What Sings In The Blood
Info / Notes / Links: although this is somewhat standard heavy rock it is actually really funny! the songs are completely tongue in cheek and have a great mix of styles. (http://www.myspace.com/ludorock)

Title: Apex
Info / Notes / Links: rootsy female led folk music. not that different than a most folk music, she has a nice twang and slide guitars. suggested for play on folkcetera. (http://www.lynnmilesmusic.com/home.html)

Title: King Night
Info / Notes / Links: electro-pop with a some soul and breathy beats. a hint of darkness that reminds me of depeche mode or the killers. good for daydream dance party. (http://www.markronson.co.uk)

Title: Grey Eyes
Info / Notes / Links: fairly wild jazz, centered around the leader's fairly wild electric guitar (she really likes to mess with pitch). it's not quite as crazed as I expected it to be and it spans a variety of moods. (http://www.myspace.com/maryhalvorsontrio)

Title: Who's We?
Info / Notes / Links: i'm actually surprised how many elements of lo-fi surf-rock costa brings on board giving it a feel more akin to harlan t. bobo than matt costa's usual dose of contemporary happy indie music. (http://www.myspace.com/mattcostamusic)

Title: The Secret Sisters
Info / Notes / Links: well-woven beats with a little bit of a slow hip-hop flare but kept eccentric and fun. kind of like hot chip. good for her royal opinion. (http://www.myspace.com/maximumballoon)

Title: Sube Azul
Info / Notes / Links: fairly standard singer-songwriter music that's super simple, nice, polite and mellow. (http://www.myspace.com/themigrantmusic)

Title: Estudando a Bossa Nordeste Plaza
Info / Notes / Links: clean southern rock n roll with honesty embedded into garage obscurity. off duty trip might want to give it a try (http://www.myspace.com/themoaners)

Title: 50 Years of Dr. Martens
Info / Notes / Links: heavy rap-metal with gnarly guitar riffs and some gently used synths for a different touch6 (http://www.mushroomhead.com)

Title: BuggedOut! Presents Suck My Deck Mixed By Friendly Fires
Info / Notes / Links: arabic electronic fusion music. definitely not like your standard world music.  (http://www.myspace.com/natachaatlasofficial)

Title: The Roots of Chicha 2: Psychedelic Cumbias From Peru
Info / Notes / Links: best desription would be fusion electronica. they have everything from tango, funk, bossa nova and so on fused with electronic beats. it's crazy stuff. recommended for alternative to what and road pops. (http://www.myspace.com/nortec)

Title: Twilights
Info / Notes / Links: crazy psychedellic music with a ton of weird isntrumetns and no tempo, no vocals. kind of like a crazier gang gang dance. (http://www.myspace.com/nymph2012)

Artist: Working For A Nuclear Free City
Title: Jojo Burger Tempest
Info / Notes / Links: enjoyable power pop with walls of melodious guitar and prominent pop vocals. kind of like ben folds with a little more feedback. good for instant gratification revoked. (http://www.myspace.com/paperlionsmusic)

Title: Young The Giant
Info / Notes / Links: this retro sounding piece of experimental rock is a heroine injected drone with monophonic melaise. completely out there and great for failed pilot. (http://www.visitation-rites.com/tag/phantom-payne-days/)

Title: Boy
Info / Notes / Links: seriously! all covers of kids tv show theme songs in METAL. it's so rad. mind grapes - watch out. i think rich l. could get away with playing it too (i just have a hunch) (http://www.myspace.com/powerglove)

Title: Furniture Music
Notes: a very post-punk charm over-rides the album with catchy garage-styled ditties all over the album. great for aubrey's shindig. (http://www.myspace.com/amanitabloom)

Title: Bees
Notes: fun and exceedingly happy lo-fi indie-pop with nothing but naive charm. similar to belle and sebastian. good for daydream dance party. (http://www.myspace.com/artichoketheband)

Title: Down There
Notes: a freaky off-shoot of animal collective with electronic infusions but still very much like the animal collective. (http://www.myspace.com/aveytaregator)

Title: Baptized In Blood
Notes: fast thrash metal with absolutely soaring guitar riffs and head-bangin' moments on almost every track. some things may be good for electric ladyland or mind grapes while megawatt may enjoy some other tracks too. (http://www.myspace.com/baptizedinblood)

Title: Mirepoix and Smoke
Notes: undeniably charming singer-songwriter indie tunes with banjo-work hitting just the right chords to accompany the haunting and cryptic songs. great for mind folk'd and william tell. (http://www.myspace.com/benweavermusic)

Title: Panorama
Notes: happy indie songs with an excellent range that utilizes electronics on some tracks and more traditional blues-rock on others. the overall result is incredibly entertaining and catchy. good for am mixtape, soap box and more. (http://www.myspace.com/birdsbatteries)

Title: Sun In The Day Moon At Night
Notes: country blues meets the indie rock realm for a different twist of the lime. It certainly takes on a heavy roots flair in the instrumentation but uses a more rock structure to mold the songs. (http://www.myspace.com/theblack)

Title: Four
Notes: happy go-lucky alternative indie-rock music perfect for hand-clapping and partying. great for any daytime show and the two and two ain't five show. (http://www.myspace.com/bleutopia)

Title: Words Words Words
Notes: completely irreverent and politically incorrect comedy that's pretty humorous. (http://www.boburnham.com/)

Title: Killing Club
Notes: a sober, spaghetti western kind of album featuring santana-esque horn sections and a slight nick cave attitude. recommended for up all night and the house blend. (http://www.myspace.com/bucketboys)

Title: Analog Drift
Notes: funky break-beat tunes that are great for a classy, yet alternative, night in. great for am mixtape and fat beat diet. (http://www.myspace.com/chicomann)

Title: The Preview
Notes: while doing quite well around north america, chiddy bang are not your typical hip-hop. it has some good, chopped up beats and interesting samples (mgmt?)...  (http://www.myspace.com/chiddybang)

Title: Songs of The Year: Vol. 1
Notes: smooth singer-songwriter tunes with a diverse range of composition from folk to more dreamy indie kind of stuff. (http://www.clearoddick.com/)

Title: Turning On
Notes: adorable pop music drowned in fuzzy distortion and elegant simplicity. great for singing along to and good for play on twilight banter and aubrey's shindig. (http://www.myspace.com/cloudnothings)

Title: Keep Me in Mind
Notes: a modern post-punk band with influences such as joy division or the cure. good and simple rock music with terribly melancholy songs. good for halfway home and up all night. (http://www.myspace.com/thecompanies)

Title: Exilarch
Notes: moody dark-wave ballads taking inspiration from west-asian countries and new age music. good for bassackwards. (http://www.myspace.com/conjureone)
original singer-songwriter tunes with an intelligent depth and beauty. reflective of the wilderness. good for folkcetera. (http://davephillipsland.com)

Title: Cardiography
Notes: cute folk-rock featuring driving beats and gentle harmonies. great for get folked. (http://www.myspace.com/davidvertesi)

Title: Daily Dance
Notes: wild and crazy experimental mayhem! percussion seems to lead the maddening chaos with sounds of instruments, static noise and sounds following close behind. great for white lodge/black lodge and noise (note, this is sort of a re-release but does contain one extra track not appearing on any earlier releases... cool)

Title: Ensemble Resonance
Notes: experimental neo-classical music that uses female operatic vocals to create eerie sounds, resonances and moods. good for that's classical? and outside the lines.

Title: National Ransom
Notes: a pop flavoured americana album with terrific composition and altogether catchy tunage. (http://www.elviscostello.info/)

Title: Undercard
Notes: dominated by darnielle's distinctive songwriting that takes a gripping hold throughout this album and bruno provides apt arrangement where necessary. very gripping and entertaining. perfect for my public shame. (http://www.mergerecords.com/blog/2010/08/the-extra-lens-announce-merge-debut/)

Title: Live at Roundhouse London
Notes: keeping the reggae slow and smooth, this live album takes a step back on electronics pursuing a much more acoustic dub and reggae angle so much so that it would fit pretty well on good character requirement. (http://www.fatfreddysdrop.com/)

Title: Floored By Four
Notes: psychedelic free jazz exploring long intervals of groove-less drone then breaking into crazy psych experiments.  (http://chimeramusic.com/fxf.html)

Title: Red Door 2nd Floor
Notes: wonderful instrumentation creates a gypsy-folk kitchen party. takes while to get into the really groovin' tracks, but its worth the wait. (http://www.myspace.com/freemandrethekitchenparty)

Title: Ghost Factory
Notes: here's some wild, roots-inspired songs that knows no bounds. it takes on more than just folk by using more punk-like structures played very-well on acoustic stringed instruments. good for via lactea caboose and the two and two ain't five show. (http://www.myspace.com/aghostfactory)

Title: Kigali Y' Izahabu
Notes: simple rwandan tunes with an endearing lo-fi quality that almost makes them sound like a daniel johnston from across the sea. (http://www.myspace.com/deadoceans)

Title: Leche
Notes: taking a goth-folk angle, these songs of towering string arrangements that make the songs super dramatic. great for mind folk'd and katharsis or william tell. (http://www.myspace.com/gregoryandthehawk)

Title: Anthems For Doomed Youth
Notes: absolutely adorable dream-pop for the hopeless romantic with songs of lust and scandals. good for daydream dance party and saturday's ladies. (http://www.myspace.com/thehighdials)

Title: The Hope Slide
Notes: ambient and gloomy tunes with a grungy, ethereal and operatic vibe to them. it's kind of difficult to describe but there's lots of unharmonic melodies pushing woefully against angst-ridden female vocals and oddly paced drum-machine loops. may be something for bassackwards. (http://www.myspace.com/thehopeslide)

Title: Avec Mes Mec EP
Notes: killer dance-pop with deep bass-grooves with infectious rhythm! great for daydream dance party and what will the neighbours think? (http://www.myspace.com/dashumans)

Title: Another Man's Treasure
Notes: weepy, lush electro-punk music with incredibly odd experiments into genres like calypso. strange, quirky and fun. (http://www.myspace.com/imarobot)

Title: Lamentations
Notes: a blend of cultural and musical styles. Predominately consisting of compositions for the clarinet but taking on very contemporary kinds of gypsy music. good for that's classical? (http://www.myspace.com/jamesfalzone)

Title: In Our Time
Notes: groovey and pretty eccentric folk music with some pretty brave explorations for a roots genre but still some more traditional tunes as well. (http://www.myspace.com/jaysparrowpage)

Title: Superhuman Heart
Notes: funky electronic laid underneath a play between girl and guy for something sounding like wildbirds and peacedrums or something a little more spacey. really neat. good for my public shame or daydream dance party or up for it. (http://www.myspace.com/jedandlucia)

Title: Knee Deep
Notes: dance ready pop songs heavy on the synth and beats. a little bit on the colder side a little washed out. showing definite homage to bands like love inc. and ray parker jr. for fans of chromeo. I'd recommend it to minima sensibilia. (http://www.myspace.com/jenocidemusic)

Title: The Falcon Lake Incident
Notes: positive and catchy folk-rock ballads sung with good-humour and dreamy melodies. really nice for soap box and double entendre. (http://www.jimbryson.org/)

Title: Cluck Old Hen
Notes: a quite rootsy album with hints of southern cajun inspiration and east coast traditional music. good for south louisiana gumbo. (http://www.joelfafard.com/)

Title: Tree Of Mystery
Notes: supremely smooth and groovy soul songs. absolutely perfect for am mixtape. (http://www.myspace.com/kabanjak)

Title: Absolute Dissent
Notes: post-punk music with lots of electronics giving it an industrial edge with hard-hitting, catchy bass lines. great for bassackwards and electric ladyland.  (http://www.myspace.com/killingjokeofficial)

Title: Last Night in Nashville
Notes: a swingin' rockabilly stomper with 14 upbeat country tunes. perfect for tombstone after dark. (http://kingmakers.ca/)

Title: Eleven Songs
Notes: pleasant and gentle indie-folk songs with a naive beauty played with simple guitar and off-key vocalizations. (http://www.myspace.com/chrisyangchrisyang)

Title: Man of Leisure
Notes: experimental indie-folk music that at times really hits the mark and at other times tends almost too much toward ordinary folk. luckily, most of it is pretty wild and very beautiful. good for daytime shows. (http://www.myspace.com/andrewbarker)

Title: Long Story Short EP
Notes: hot hip-hop tracks with smooth samples laying down sexy beats. a couple good tracks for knotted roots of zarif. (http://www.myspace.com/bowenlen)

Title: Brighter Days
Notes: revolution ready reggae music with some calypso vibes and other more dancehall ready songs. whatever the style, the sounds are always smooth, well put together and poignant. good for level the vibes. (http://www.myspace.com/lyndonjohnx)

Title: As U Were
Notes: relevant rap, some of it is pretty slick but it is really witty and sharp stuff. good for mental illness. (http://www.myspace.com/lyricsborn)

Title: Black
Notes: dark, ambient industrial music that goes back to earlier influences like skinny puppy and einsterzende neubauten. good for noise and bassackwards. (http://www.myspace.com/maqlumusic)

Title: False Flag
Notes: alternative post-punk tunes complete with fuzzy guitar and long guitar solos. great for shows like halfway home and aubrey's shindig. (http://www.myspace.com/themarkinside)

Title: It's Always Stormy In Tillamook
Notes: cheerful indie tunes with a child-like naivety woven with an older outlook. some songs are really fun others are fairly ordinary sort of mellow songs. (http://www.myspace.com/megdia)

Title: Self Control
Notes: kind of silly and young indie dance-rock with a peter, bjorn and john feel. weirdo songwriting and crazy style makes the tracks feel super hot and addictive. good for daydream dance party and up for it. (http://www.myspace.com/themercynow)

Title: Mt. Desolation
Notes: not incredibly cheerful, not incredibly catchy but still very well played and well written. it's simple music. (http://www.myspace.com/mtdesolation)

Title: Leather Silk
Notes: pure rock music in many ways. good, catchy rhythm and strong melodies create a fun sound. good for aubrey's shindig (http://www.myspace.com/iluvmymymy)

Title: New Channel
Notes: beautiful ambient-electronic recordings with echoing depth and feeling to them. long, drawn out pieces chart territories of sound lost in space and far reaches of earth. perfect for katharsis. (http://radio3.cbc.ca/#/bands/New-Channel)

Title: The New Family
Notes: cleverly spun country tunes with saloon echo on the guitar that conjures ideas of tumbling weeds. good for tombstone and my public shame. (http://www.myspace.com/thenewfamily)

Title: Icons
Notes: fairly in your face punk rock, a little hint of lo-fi but mostly just riotous punk rock. (http://www.myspace.com/nmbmusic)

Title: Metallic Spheres
Notes: a spacey, psychedelic jam up the alley of ambient electronic nerds. very chill sounds laden with echoey guitar. good for funk senden. (http://www.davidgilmour.com/)

Title: A View Of The Sky
Notes: fascinatingly rich singer-songwriter indie songs with allusions to bands like neutral milk hotel. good for soap box and william tell. (http://www.myspace.com/paleo)

Title: Fog Like This
Notes: clever use of glitchy electronics, crooning jazz vocals and a pop music sensibility gives this album a few very interesting and engaging ditties. not all are winners but there's some great catches. good for minima sensobilia and twilight banter. (http://www.myspace.com/perilellemusic)

Title: Liasons
Notes: lo-fi singer-songwriter tunes with a jazzy flair that is hip and heartwarming all at the same time. this lady has some serious ideas to share in a subtle way. great for my public shame, twilight banter and white lodge/black lodge. (http://pigeonsband.com/)

Title: Hope And Despair
Notes: smooth, deep and heartfelt soul with a trip-hop kind of feel but a little less dark and a little less electronic. great for those who like jaga jazzist. great for road pops and am mixtape and radio boys. (http://www.myspace.com/radiocitizen)

Title: Fire Works
Notes: lo-fi punk rock played loud, not overly fast, but with a good edge and a decent growl. (http://www.myspace.com/thesaintecatherines)

Title: Running Wild
Notes: self-proclaimed as a hip celtic band and that couldn't be truer. melding traditional celtic tunes with terry sheridan's own composition gives you something fun, upbeat and really interesting. nocturntable could play it and maybe even breaking the tethers. (http://www.thesheridanband.com/blog/)

Title: Songs About Girls & Outer Space
Notes: grungy noise-rock with a definite '90s sort of feel to the songs. good for instant gratification revoked. (http://www.myspace.com/sleepins)

Title: Blackouts
Notes: a post hardcore band with a certain pop feel similar to alexisonfire. quite heavy, youthful and incredibly interesting. (http://www.myspace.com/thesnipsmusic)

Title: The Age of Adz
Notes: really beautiful indie-pop incorporating many sounds and innovative styles. also, lots of electronic bits and pieces collaged together. good for daydream dance party. (http://www.sufjan.com/)

Title: Destination Christmas!
Notes: incredibly funny, exceedingly humorous. who are we kidding? it's fred schneider from the b-52s reinventing rock lobster with a christmas theme. HILARIOUS. good for am i right and my allergy to the fans. (http://www.myspace.com/thesuperions)

Title: Salt March
Notes: heavy alternative rock, maxed to 11, utilizing classic structures to build driving songs with a hint of '90's grunge and punk-rock. there may be a few songs good for bikesheviks. (http://www.myspace.com/swanrock)

Title: Until One
Notes: a classic house meets disco album harkening the late 70s happy-go-lovely gay scenes. good for the mix up and sunday night groove school. (http://www.myspace.com/swedishhousemafia)

Title: Thunder Equals Lava
Notes: heavy crowd-pleasing rock and roll in all its glory and incredibly witty lyrics... of course, what do expect from andy sparacino from the a-team? so definitely made for my allergy to the fans. (http://visar.ca/thunderequalslava/)

Title: Water-Color Crayon
Notes: fairly mediocre and juvenile hip-hop funk music composed almost entirely on sequencers or machines of that sort. (http://www.myspace.com/thetreetrunkfunk)

Title: Heresie
Notes: eerie, neo-classical music that combines the psychedelic, rock and chamber music resulting in a fascinating and interesting experience. good for noise and that's classical? (http://www.myspace.com/universzero)

Title: Caves
Notes: crazy progressive punk... maybe rock. it's definitely wild and a lot of fun! good for breaking the tethers. (http://www.myspace.com/uzjsmedoma)

Title: Bassments of Badmen Vo. 2
Notes: mostly canadian hip-hop on this compilation spanning a variety of hip-hop styles. some really cool work on here though. good for mental illness. (http://handsolorecords.com/releases/badmen2/)

Artist: Various (From The Tank 17 - Unreleased Tracks From The Windsor Music Collective)
Title: From The Tank
Notes: the majority of songs are mediocre folk or country songs but there are definitely a couple of gems snuck in between the lines here that some of the day time shows may find appealing. (http://sharktankpro.com/fromthetank/)

Title: Apparat DJ-Kicks
Notes: lovely, chill-out electro-mix with a selection of mellow songs great for late nights. good for translucent dreams. (http://www.myspace.com/apparat)

Title: Death Seat
Notes: haunting folk songs played fairly clean and pure. although there's nothing too catchy with these tunes they are well-written and quite endearing with interesting work on the compositions. good for folkcetera and some morning shows. (http://www.myspace.com/woodenwand)

Title: Sharrafouni
Notes: traditional arabic songstress. (http://www.myspace.com/zeinjundi)

Title: Allo Darlin'
Info / Notes / Links: excessively adorable twee-pop that can certainly attribute their sound to love-lost summers and lo-fi garage rigs. they'll melt your heart with brilliant execution. (http://www.myspace.com/allodarlin)

Title: Split Heart
Info / Notes / Links: with a witty lo-fi flare and a clever use of vintage organs, anna re-creates cute singer-songwriter songs speaking of youthfulness but with a mature side to the songs as well. (http://www.myspace.com/annabullard)

Title: The City That Sleeps
Info / Notes / Links: here's a markedly new wave sound along the lines of modern english or tears for fears, spiced slightly with more recent progressions in indie music like melancholy layers of melody on guitars and keyboard and some pretty driving beats. (http://www.myspace.com/asilentfilm)

Title: Live, Volume 3
Info / Notes / Links: well-written and contagious indie-folk songs who's energy is taken up a notch with the really excited crowd (this is a live recording). (http://www.theavettbrothers.com/us/home)

Title: Wildstyle
Info / Notes / Links: heavy and tripped out electronic rave music with whomping bass but, in usual bassnectar fashion, incorporating other elements of rock and even folk... (http://www.myspace.com/bassnectar)

Title: Write About Love
Info / Notes / Links: this release is actually pretty monotonic with a hint towards cuteness and kind a vaguely summer feel. (http://www.myspace.com/thebandbelleandsebastian)

Title: Penny Sparkle
Info / Notes / Links: subdued, echo drowned rock songs with the usual hints of ambient electronics. this album goes in an almost stereolab direction. good for daydream dance party and up for it. (http://www.myspace.com/blonderedhead)

Title: Fire Like This
Info / Notes / Links: a very uk-punk-dance-rock sound heavier than a female led franz ferdinand or the bravery but still infectious with energy. good for electric ladyland. (http://www.myspace.com/bloodredshoes)

Title: Some Concerns Regarding This Revolt
Info / Notes / Links: pure anthemic punk-rock ready for mosh-pit mayhem. (http://www.myspace.com/broadcastzero)

Title: Mirror
Info / Notes / Links: tenor-led jazz quartet. the performances are largely on the mellow/ballad side of things and are split between covers and originals. unfortunately, most of them are kinda drab. things really only come to life/get interesting with the last two tracks. last track has vocals-spoken word. (http://www.charleslloyd.com/)

Title: Getting' Personial
Info / Notes / Links: wild rock music that uses many odd time signatures, other-worldly sounds and lots of effects. really wild. good for failed pilot. (http://www.myspace.com/clintonmachine)

Title: Alive As You Are
Info / Notes / Links: sounding more southern than west-coast, Darker My Love bring good rock and roll to your ears with luscious melodies full of flirtatious effectuality. so many influences, some of which include bob dylan (http://www.myspace.com/darkermylove)

Title: Halcyon Digest
Info / Notes / Links: you could call it surf-garage but it's by far the weirdest you'll hear! for those who might like ariel pink. good for william tell. (http://www.myspace.com/deerhunter)

Title: Nukes De Papel
Info / Notes / Links: a slight hint of spanish influence comes over these endearing ditties that are quite upbeat and delightful. good for shows like instant gratification revoked, soap box derby and up for it. (http://www.myspace.com/myspacedepedro)

Title: Contaminated Waters
Info / Notes / Links: impossible to categorize, these psychedelic break-beatsters use so many styles your head will be spinning. the closest comparison is kid koala. pretty fun. recommended for dave sh. (http://www.myspace.com/diegothedissidents)

Title: Future Retro
Info / Notes / Links: ridiculously danceable tracks to get your party going. deep electro-beats stir up memories of daft punk and chemical brothers. really fun. good for late nights. (http://www.djdan.com/)

Title: Two New Songs By Doug Hoyer
Info / Notes / Links: amazingly fun singer-songwriter numbers with an endearing pep. for fans of twee!!! (http://doughoyer.bandcamp.com/)

Title: Dubber Side Of The Moon
Info / Notes / Links: swelling and very reggae-styled dub music with a psychedelic edginess to it. some songs could work on dubble bounce, some for road pops too. (http://www.myspace.com/easystarallstars)

Title: Pop Negro
Info / Notes / Links: dreamy indie-pop tunes over slower hip-hop styled beats sung in spanish. pretty darn rad. (http://www.myspace.com/elguincho)

Title: Eskmo
Info / Notes / Links: a definite yes! this electronic romp through wonderland is deep, heavy, strange and eerie full of great beats alongside IDM-like structure. good for translucent dreams. (http://www.myspace.com/eskmo)

Title: Sincerely, F&M
Info / Notes / Links: incredibly contemporary folk music. some of the songs are a little too melodramatic, i'd say but the duo here are incredibly talented songwriters and incorporate some interesting elements into their song-structures. (http://www.myspace.com/fandmtheband)

Title: As I Call You Down
Info / Notes / Links: catchy indie-folk tunes swelling with emotions and full compositions. good for twilight banter. (http://fistfulofmercy.com/)

Title: Terra Fire
Info / Notes / Links: real damn doomy metal meets spastic hardcore punk. intense overdriven guitar plays bone-chilling riffs while vocalist screams like the under taker is around the corner. in-tense. great for rage cage (http://www.myspace.com/thefuckingwrath)

Title: Aim and Ignite
Info / Notes / Links: you couldn't find a more apt name for this band. playful melodies and lyrics to match that are both humorous and charming. (http://www.myspace.com/fun)

Title: Beeps
Info / Notes / Links: totally lo-fi and amusingly experimental that instantly appeal to the teen in me attending very cool, alternative battles of the bands. the overall sound is pretty west coast (think seattle and portland stuff on k recs). (http://radio3.cbc.ca/#/bands/Sunbear)

Title: The Getby
Info / Notes / Links: picking out the grooviest beats for smooth raps to flow over.  maybe something for knotted roots. (http://www.facebook.com/pages/The-Get-By/140791832754)

Artist: Ghost of a Saber Tooth Tiger, The
Title: Acoustic Sessions
Info / Notes / Links: a strange feeling starts to swell as the music plays on, they're weird, they use simple song structures with complicated lyrics incredibly morbid and mystical. (http://theghostofasabertoothedtiger.com/)

Title: Hello Sailor
Info / Notes / Links: some songs are gypsy punk but overall the album is good ol' uk punk inspired by the ocean's roar. great for music to my ears and i can even imagine daydream dance party getting down with it. (http://www.myspace.com/girlsgirlsgirlsuk)

Title: Ring
Info / Notes / Links: with a wispy, icelandic sound (althought she's from the us) this little lady has a ton of creativity and feeling portrayed in her sounds. she's similar to florence and the machine, jj or fever ray. good for twilight banter. (http://www.myspace.com/glasssser)

Title: Made Of Metal
Info / Notes / Links: I doubt you'll be disappointed with this complete 70s metal throw back. it's epic, anthemic and classic. good for rage cage. (http://www.robhalford.com)

Title: Holloh
Info / Notes / Links: dark-wave songs taking inspiration from operatic-metal (maybe) or depressing shoegaze music. super strange but also very familiar, like something from a decade ago's less than happy grunge scene. (http://www.myspace.com/hollohinside)

Title: Album
Info / Notes / Links: fun, danceable and cute indie music for brightening the sadder days. these fun gents will bring a ray of light to any cloudy day. (http://www.myspace.com/hoodedfang)

Title: Fantastic Static
Info / Notes / Links: inspired by post-punk era music but incorporating aspects of heavy metal and straight punk as well for an interesting mix. good for aubrey's shindig. (http://www.myspace.com/hotchachahotchacha)

Title: Interpol
Info / Notes / Links: returning to their colder, guitar-driven roots where sadness drips of every word. great for new classics and breaking techniques (http://www.myspace.com/interpol)

Title: Catalyst
Info / Notes / Links: a variety of styles are touched upon here (eg experimental, straight-ahead, mellow/smooth, fusion,etc), sometimes within the same track (eg #10). some things work better than others but, overall, its pretty good. strong electric bass throughout. (http://www.myspace.com/jeffkingsaxmusic)

Title: E.P.ilogue On Opposite Day
Info / Notes / Links: comical punk songs kept incredibly simple and detuned. for fans of atom and his package. (http://www.myspace.com/keepmesafeband)

Title: Apple Core
Info / Notes / Links: check this rootsy chick out 'cause she's got an amazing knack for songwriting that's funny and really, really folksy. good for the two and two ain't five show and the folk shows. (http://www.myspace.com/winterkendl)

Title: You Are A Secret, And You Must Never Tell It
Info / Notes / Links: an album quite all over the map for styles. monotonic vocals make it a bizarre listen. really undefinable and pleasurable if only for its weirdness. (http://www.myspace.com/kitesoverhead)

Title: The Booze Sessions
Info / Notes / Links: irreverent punk-rock. most of the songs sound pretty similar, full of swears, booze and sex. not bad for what it is. graveyard riot could get some spins from it. (http://www.myspace.com/theluckyonespunk)

Title: Silent Movies
Info / Notes / Links: solo guitar pieces, mostly electric, some acoustic written for films. things are fairly atmospheric, pretty much mood music. (http://www.marcribot.com/)

Title: Teflon Child
Info / Notes / Links: super fun bit-chopped dance-punk, like a lot of stuff on the retard disco label and stereo total... so funny! great for dj ninja (bryson) and nathan t. (http://www.myspace.com/mathiasmental)

Title: After Hours: Moonlamps & Other Ballads
Info / Notes / Links: this cd is a compliation of tunes from other Matthias Lupri Cds. it's supposed to be a collection of ballad-type performances featuring Lupris vibes. most of the cd is like this but the best tracks are the ones that come out on the eerie, atmospheric side. (http://www.matthiaslupri.com/)

Title: Tropsicle
Info / Notes / Links: lively and joyful power-pop peppered with the joys of living under the sea. lovely, strange sounds creep into songs giving it a sound akin to Islands (the sea themed bands). good for breaking techniques and radio boys. (http://www.myspace.com/mermaidsatl)

Title: Fortune
Info / Notes / Links: renaissance inspired songs with an overwhelming sadness and reflection. excellent use of woodwinds over percussion and acoustic guitar. great for katharsis. (http://www.myspace.com/midlake)

Title: Betweenwhile
Info / Notes / Links: mostly typical out there AUM Fidelity jazz. Some of the tracks border on normal and are kind of mellow, at least by AUM Fidelity standards. (http://www.myspace.com/snugglestencil)

Title: Circles
Info / Notes / Links: woeful and lively alt-country kind of going for the cuff-the-duke or the zolas thing but with more stripped down instrumentation (guitar, drums and vocals) (http://www.myspace.com/nervouswrecked)

Title: Sweet Little Thing b/w I Got Nuthin'
Info / Notes / Links: pure, in your face rock from start to finish. buzzing guitar fails to let up on its intensity and the other musicians do not fail to follow suit.

Title: Pawn Shop
Info / Notes / Links: psychedelic instrumental music showing influences from jazz, funk and hip-hop. good for some of the morning shows. (http://pawnshop.bandcamp.com/)

Title: Peripheral Vision
Info / Notes / Links: a collection of somewhat tricky jazz tunes. it's not too wild but not too mellow, just a bit off straight ahead jazz. (http://www.myspace.com/peripheralvisionmusic)

Title: Dragon Slayer
Info / Notes / Links: only describable as indie-hip-hop. fairly down-beat, high on cute and super charming and imaginative.  (http://www.myspace.com/pigeonjohn)

Title: Break Failure
Info / Notes / Links: jazzy, soulful and very soft mood music for chilling out at the end of a long day. it takes some interesting directions toward metal and discord but stays fairly calm for the most part. may be something for white lodge/black lodge. (http://rowanconverse.bandcamp.com/)

Title: Litanies
Info / Notes / Links: droning noise-rock featuring walls of crushing guitar most prominently and pretty psychedelic vocals and sounds filling out the rest. (http://www.myspace.com/baths)

Title: Telephantasm
Info / Notes / Links: a compilation of soundgarden stuff... what you'd expect. (http://www.SoundgardenWorld.com/)

Title: Raise Up Your Head
Info / Notes / Links: spastic, lo-fi rock music with a late 90's kind of vibe. not as catchy as the thermals but the same idea. (http://www.myspace.com/thestormalongs)

Title: Off Duty
Info / Notes / Links: extra-terrestrial sounds locked into tripped out grooves weirder still for the pure endurance (each track about 10 minutes) (http://www.myspace.com/sunaraw)

Title: Moonbath
Info / Notes / Links: really beautiful indie-folk for settling down to in a cool cafe or sitting around a campfire. lustful vocals are accompanied by a deep assortment of instrumentation. (http://radio3.cbc.ca/#/bands/Sunbear)

Title: The Inevitable Past Is The Future Forgotten
Info / Notes / Links: sprawling alternative rock with a subdued winter-ness about it. a definite likeness to pinback (no surprise there) (http://www.myspace.com/threemilepilot)

Title: Baby We Can Work It Out
Info / Notes / Links: silly and cute music that's lively and positive with aspects of coastal reggae as well as experimental-pop sounds in the lines of apples in stereo. cool for road pops. (http://www.myspace.com/timchadandsherry)

Title: Songs For Singles
Info / Notes / Links: what starts off has heavy, growling metal turns into droning but loud instrumental rock that's pleasingly intricate and complex. (http://www.myspace.com/torche)

Title: Mixed Race
Info / Notes / Links: a constantly evolving sound held together with imaginative electronics and groovy beats. (http://www.myspace.com/trickola)

Title: Fubar II: Music From The Original Motion Picture
Info / Notes / Links: rock and roll for drinking to and having a really fun time. (http://www.fubar-themovie.com/)

Title: I'm Here Soundtrack
Info / Notes / Links: charming, unusual and very interesting indie songs that are surprisingly good for a soundtrack (i haven't seen the movie though... but they seem like they'd work). (http://consequenceofsound.net/2010/08/11/spike-jonzes-im-here-soundtrack-alive-with-indie-acts/)

Title: Radioclit Presents African Dance Music Anthems
Info / Notes / Links: lively african dance music from various countries and with varying styles. (http://www.nialler9.com/2010/09/23/radioclit-present-sound-club-secousse-african-dance-compilation/)

Title: Lack Of Color
Info / Notes / Links: a diy pop-punk band with a great rock sound that's just gritty enough. (http://www.myspace.com/vendettaskies)

Title: The Fool
Info / Notes / Links: mystical music that is both sparse yet deeply moving. these three girls create eerie, echoey sounds that are great for twilight banter and double entendre preserves. (http://www.myspace.com/worldwartour)

Title: We Were Lovers
Info / Notes / Links: here's a real pop sensibility and a truly breathtaking method of music making. the vocals washed out in slow synthetic melodies remind me of new order. good for halfway home. (http://www.myspace.com/wewereloversmusic)

Title: Dust Lane
Info / Notes / Links: dark, ambient pop music built on solid abstract washes of sound and monotonic words. recomended for katharsis. (http://www.myspace.com/yanntierseninprogress)

Title: Boy
Info / Notes / Links: seriously! all covers of kids tv show theme songs in METAL. it's so rad. mind grapes - watch out. i think rich l. could get away with playing it too (i just have a hunch) (http://www.myspace.com/powerglove)
